490
00:31:21,300 --> 00:31:24,800
Do you believe Satan walks the earth
in a fleshly form?

491
00:31:24,800 --> 00:31:28,200
That Satan can occupy the souls of men?

492
00:31:28,200 --> 00:31:30,600
And he's just getting started.

493
00:31:31,300 --> 00:31:35,600
There's gonna be a lot more dead
before it's over.

494
00:31:35,600 --> 00:31:38,200
Hundreds. Maybe thousands.

495
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:04,300
They still got you working outta this shithole?
I don't believe it.

496
00:32:04,300 --> 00:32:07,400
It ain't much but it's been months
since a boss has been able to find me.

497
00:32:07,500 --> 00:32:11,000
You still have some interest
in Marlo Stanfield, right?

498
00:32:12,900 --> 00:32:14,900
That's his cell.

499
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:16,800
He stopped using cellphones.

500
00:32:16,900 --> 00:32:19,800
Ellis, how?

501
00:32:19,900 --> 00:32:22,500
Police work, detective.

502
00:32:36,100 --> 00:32:39,100
- Yo, this the High Hat?
- Say what?

503
00:32:39,100 --> 00:32:43,400
Y'all still open for carryout?
I want some of that pepper steak.

504
00:32:43,400 --> 00:32:45,000
Wrong number, fool.

505
00:32:49,100 --> 00:32:51,900
I wish I could tell you it's a shock

506
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:53,800
but it seems to happen in every city

507
00:32:53,900 --> 00:32:56,600
where we get us a place
inside the power structure

508
00:32:56,600 --> 00:32:59,800
- And we become targets.
- I know you're right.

509
00:32:59,800 --> 00:33:04,100
It's not a black-white thing.
The State's Attorney, Mr. Bond, he's black.

510
00:33:04,200 --> 00:33:06,500
But if it serves his purpose -

511
00:33:06,500 --> 00:33:09,400
gets his name in the news,
ups his profile -

512
00:33:09,400 --> 00:33:12,100
he'll do whatever the folks
pulling the strings want.

513
00:33:12,100 --> 00:33:15,300
Whether it be character assassination,

514
00:33:15,300 --> 00:33:17,500
tie the noose in the rope, whatever.

515
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:19,500
But they picked the wrong man this time.

516
00:33:19,500 --> 00:33:22,500
- They must not heard about you, Senator.
- I don't run from a fight.

517
00:33:22,500 --> 00:33:24,300
- I know that.
- The people know.

518
00:33:24,300 --> 00:33:26,300
I'm talkin' 'bout the people now...

519
00:33:26,300 --> 00:33:29,800
The people know what I've done
for West Baltimore and this city.

520
00:33:29,900 --> 00:33:32,200
They know the battles I fight every day.

521
00:33:32,200 --> 00:33:34,900
They know these charges
ain't nothing but B.S.

522
00:33:34,900 --> 00:33:36,700
Hold it now, it's radio.

523
00:33:36,700 --> 00:33:38,500
I gotta hold my tongue, I know.

524
00:33:38,500 --> 00:33:41,200
I don't want nobody pullin' y'all's license,

525
00:33:41,200 --> 00:33:43,200
so I can't say it like I feel it.

526
00:33:43,300 --> 00:33:46,000
But I wanted to come here
on your show tonight -

527
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:49,100
and thank you so much
for the opportunity, my brother -

528
00:33:49,100 --> 00:33:53,300
but I wanted your listeners to be
the first to hear it from my mouth.

529
00:33:53,300 --> 00:33:55,700
I have committed no crime,

530
00:33:55,800 --> 00:33:59,100
and I am gonna keep on doing
the people's work without breaking stride.

531
00:33:59,100 --> 00:34:00,600
Thank you for that, Senator.

532
00:34:00,700 --> 00:34:04,600
And also I want everybody to know
there's going to be a gathering

533
00:34:04,600 --> 00:34:08,300
at the Mitchell courthouse
tomorrow at 2:00

534
00:34:08,300 --> 00:34:10,500
so that people can be heard on this.

535
00:34:10,500 --> 00:34:14,000
- I hope they come out in good numbers.
- 2:00 on Calvert Street.

536
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:16,900
- It's time to lift every voice.
- I heard that.

537
00:34:16,900 --> 00:34:21,300
Three detectives for a 24-hour wiretap.

538
00:34:21,300 --> 00:34:23,800
Four more in two-man surveillance teams.

539
00:34:23,800 --> 00:34:25,800
A pair of unmarked cars.

540
00:34:25,900 --> 00:34:28,200
I'm not asking the world here, Cedric.

541
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:30,600
Lester, if I had it, you'd have it.

542
00:34:30,600 --> 00:34:35,300
That's the cell number of the motherfucker
who put 22 bodies on us.

543
00:34:35,300 --> 00:34:37,700
- Go to the fucking mayor!
- I've been to the mayor.

544
00:34:37,700 --> 00:34:41,200
I've been to him on my knees twice.
Once for your case, remember?

545
00:34:41,300 --> 00:34:44,600
And all I could bring back was
two men to work Clay Davis.

546
00:34:44,600 --> 00:34:48,600
And yesterday, for the serial killer
that homicide was working, two men only.

547
00:34:48,600 --> 00:34:51,700
I've done my job.
I've gone up the ladder every time.

548
00:34:51,800 --> 00:34:55,300
But if a fucking serial killer
can't bring back more than a couple detectives,

549
00:34:55,300 --> 00:34:59,300
what the hell does it matter
that you have a fresh phone number?

550
00:35:06,100 --> 00:35:09,600
More manpower's been assigned,
according to the P.I.O.

551
00:35:12,100 --> 00:35:13,800
And?

552
00:35:13,800 --> 00:35:17,700
I led with the first victim. Ex-marine.
Bronze-star in Vietnam.

553
00:35:17,700 --> 00:35:20,800
His family begged him to come home,
which he would do now and then,

554
00:35:20,800 --> 00:35:23,900
but they hadn't seen him
in a month before the murder.

555
00:35:23,900 --> 00:35:26,600
Good shit. Real good shit.

556
00:35:26,600 --> 00:35:28,500
Late, but you got
the goods, right?

557
00:35:28,500 --> 00:35:30,300
Half of these guys are whack jobs,

558
00:35:30,300 --> 00:35:32,800
the other half just want
to borrow a fin...

559
00:35:33,900 --> 00:35:36,500
But yeah, I got good stuff.

560
00:35:36,500 --> 00:35:39,300
Got a family of four under
the Hanover Street Bridge.

561
00:35:39,300 --> 00:35:42,000
Father broke down and cried
when I talked to him,

562
00:35:42,100 --> 00:35:46,000
talking about how he couldn't protect himself,
couldn't protect his kids.

563
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:48,800
Mother just kept stroking
the youngest one's blonde hair.

564
00:35:48,800 --> 00:35:50,700
- We got names on this, right?
- Yeah.

565
00:35:50,700 --> 00:35:52,600
Guy's name is...

566
00:35:54,300 --> 00:35:57,000
Boston. Nathan Levi Boston.

567
00:35:57,000 --> 00:35:59,300
OK, you got 30 inches,
if you need them.

568
00:35:59,300 --> 00:36:02,800
You're going off the front
in a package with Alma and Fletch.

569
00:36:02,800 --> 00:36:05,800
Olesker wrote a pretty damn good
column, too, for metro front.

570
00:36:05,900 --> 00:36:07,300
Go, go. Write, write.

571
00:36:07,300 --> 00:36:12,300
This serial killer is making one Baltimorean
very, very happy.

572
00:36:12,400 --> 00:36:14,100
Clay Davis.

573
00:36:14,200 --> 00:36:17,400
One news cycle, and his indictment's
gonna be off the front page.

574
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:20,200
Well, if it bleeds, it leads.

575
00:36:20,200 --> 00:36:22,000
A fucking serial killer.

576
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:24,900
I give them a sex-crazed madman
who's enough of a freak show

577
00:36:24,900 --> 00:36:28,000
to get the whole city hot and bothered
and what comes back?

578
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:30,100
One fucking detective.

579
00:36:30,100 --> 00:36:33,200
And who is it? Kima Greggs,
who should be working her triple.

580
00:36:33,200 --> 00:36:36,800
So now I can't give you her hours
without fucking up honest casework.

581
00:36:36,900 --> 00:36:39,600
Well, now it's easier, Jimmy.
We don't need as much.

582
00:36:39,600 --> 00:36:41,800
Now we need a wiretap.

583
00:36:41,800 --> 00:36:43,400
I can monitor that myself.

584
00:36:43,400 --> 00:36:46,700
Shit, anything we get up
is gonna be illegal anyway.

585
00:36:46,800 --> 00:36:48,800
So we don't want anyone getting near it.

586
00:36:48,800 --> 00:36:51,200
Sydnor, maybe. I can trust him.

587
00:36:51,200 --> 00:36:53,900
You start pulling
information off that phone,

588
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:57,600
you're gonna need at least a couple
of surveillance cars in the street.

589
00:36:57,600 --> 00:36:59,100
We'll worry when we get there.

590
00:36:59,100 --> 00:37:02,400
The important thing is that
he's making it easy for us.

591
00:37:02,500 --> 00:37:05,900
Before, with all that face-to-face,
we were gonna need what?

592
00:37:05,900 --> 00:37:07,900
Remote cameras, microphones,

593
00:37:07,900 --> 00:37:10,800
half-a-dozen guys
working surveillance 24 hours.

594
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:15,100
But now he's talking on a phone,
and I got him.

595
00:37:15,100 --> 00:37:18,700
So how do we squeeze a wiretap
out of my serial killer?

596
00:37:21,200 --> 00:37:23,300
He's gotta call someone.

597
00:37:23,300 --> 00:37:25,300
Who?

598
00:37:25,300 --> 00:37:26,800
The mayor.

599
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:28,100
Cardinal Keeler.

600
00:37:28,100 --> 00:37:30,600
Cal fucking Ripken.
Who gives a fuck?

601
00:37:33,400 --> 00:37:36,200
A bullshit number on
the paperwork to the courthouse,

602
00:37:36,200 --> 00:37:39,700
Marlo's cell number on the tap itself.

603
00:37:39,800 --> 00:37:42,200
This is fucking genius...

604
00:37:42,900 --> 00:37:44,200
Or not.

605
00:37:49,200 --> 00:37:52,200
If that's about your case,
you need to answer it.

606
00:37:52,200 --> 00:37:54,200
Remember you're working
a serial killer.

607
00:37:54,200 --> 00:37:57,400
Nah, it's my ex-wife.
Been calling all night.

608
00:37:57,400 --> 00:38:00,300
Like I got time for her fucking bullshit.

609
00:38:00,300 --> 00:38:04,700
They got to believe it's your killer calling
before they'll pay for a wiretap.

610
00:38:04,800 --> 00:38:06,400
Well, fine. Fuck it.

611
00:38:06,400 --> 00:38:09,100
Call your buddy Oscar,
tell him we need another body.

612
00:38:09,200 --> 00:38:11,500
The sick motherfucker
is gonna call Mr. Ripken

613
00:38:11,600 --> 00:38:14,200
with something only
the killer could know.

614
00:38:14,900 --> 00:38:18,600
That should shake 'em up enough
for a couple of wiretaps.

615
00:38:35,300 --> 00:38:37,500
Monk sure do like to retire early.

616
00:38:39,700 --> 00:38:41,400
Three go in and one come out.

617
00:38:41,500 --> 00:38:42,900
Better odds.

618
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:50,000
We're gonna wait on it though.
They'll get better still.

619
00:38:50,100 --> 00:38:52,900
If not tonight, then the next.

620
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:54,500
You're a patient man.

621
00:38:54,600 --> 00:38:56,100
Him too.

622
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:17,000
I tried to reach you on your cell all day.

623
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:20,200
- I called Beadie, she had no idea...
- I know. It's my fault.

624
00:39:20,200 --> 00:39:22,700
- They still up?
- Yes.

625
00:39:26,800 --> 00:39:28,100
Hey, guys.

626
00:39:28,200 --> 00:39:29,700
Hey, dad.

627
00:39:30,600 --> 00:39:34,300
Listen, Sean, I did everything I could
to get to your play tonight.

628
00:39:36,900 --> 00:39:38,200
Hey, Mike.

629
00:39:43,900 --> 00:39:45,900
It's cool. No worries.

630
00:39:47,400 --> 00:39:49,200
Your mom said you were great.

631
00:39:49,200 --> 00:39:51,100
Why don't you do it now? Let me hear it.

632
00:39:51,100 --> 00:39:55,500
I don't know. It's lame like that.
You gotta see the whole play.

633
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:05,500
What band is that?

634
00:40:05,500 --> 00:40:06,500
Dead Meadow.

635
00:40:06,600 --> 00:40:09,000
- Dead metal?
- Meadow. Dead Meadow.

636
00:40:10,800 --> 00:40:13,800
What the hell's wrong
with the Ramones?

637
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:20,000
I'll make it up next weekend.
Take 'em to the ball game.

638
00:40:20,100 --> 00:40:24,800
Hey, this is life, Jimmy.
This is the stuff that actually matters.

639
00:40:24,900 --> 00:40:27,500
- I know.
- I talked to Beadie.

640
00:40:28,600 --> 00:40:31,100
She knows she's losing you.
Like I knew.

641
00:40:31,100 --> 00:40:33,300
I'm not judging.

642
00:40:33,300 --> 00:40:36,100
I'm not saying this to hurt you.

643
00:40:36,200 --> 00:40:37,500
But she knows.

644
00:40:37,500 --> 00:40:41,000
And she's ready for it,
the way that I was ready for it.

645
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:43,600
You're drinking.
You're out all night.

646
00:40:43,600 --> 00:40:45,400
She doesn't know where you are.

647
00:40:45,400 --> 00:40:47,800
And she's no fool, Jimmy.

648
00:40:47,800 --> 00:40:51,100
I'm sad that it wasn't with me...

649
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:55,500
but I'm glad for you.

650
00:40:57,000 --> 00:40:59,600
I know, you can imagine that?

651
00:40:59,600 --> 00:41:02,100
I was glad that you found her.

652
00:41:03,700 --> 00:41:05,700
I was glad for her, even.

653
00:41:07,400 --> 00:41:11,100
For a while there, you were
happier than I've ever seen you.

654
00:41:11,100 --> 00:41:12,800
She's great.

655
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:16,100
She is.

656
00:41:17,700 --> 00:41:19,600
Don't do this.

657
00:41:39,900 --> 00:41:42,000
You all right, Bubs?

658
00:41:42,100 --> 00:41:47,000
I'm good. Except for somethin'
that's been on my mind.

659
00:41:47,100 --> 00:41:49,800
- But I see you into somethin'...
- I can take a minute.

660
00:41:49,800 --> 00:41:53,300
Need to find somethin' out.
But I don't know if I really wanna know.

661
00:41:55,700 --> 00:41:58,500
It's best to know, Bubs. I'm living proof.

662
00:41:58,500 --> 00:42:00,700
They got drugs an' shit now.

663
00:42:00,700 --> 00:42:02,500
Why's it on your mind now?

664
00:42:02,500 --> 00:42:06,300
Been volunteering down Viva House,
doin' like you told me.

665
00:42:06,300 --> 00:42:08,300
Man say he want me to serve food.

666
00:42:08,300 --> 00:42:11,300
You can. It don't travel like that.

667
00:42:11,300 --> 00:42:14,600
I know they say so, but I feel...

668
00:42:14,700 --> 00:42:16,600
I don't know.

669
00:42:16,600 --> 00:42:20,500
I went down to the clinic yesterday,
got as far as the door, but...

670
00:42:20,500 --> 00:42:23,900
- Tough to go alone.
- Yeah.

671
00:42:25,200 --> 00:42:26,900
Gimme 10 minutes.

672
00:42:29,600 --> 00:42:31,800
So, where do we take it today?

673
00:42:31,900 --> 00:42:35,000
Unless the story develops,
I think we've covered the bases.

674
00:42:35,100 --> 00:42:38,900
Alma can check on things
and see where we're at by afternoon.

675
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:40,500
You owe me a Govans story.

676
00:42:40,500 --> 00:42:43,500
And you need to get with Shane
on with that school series.

677
00:42:43,600 --> 00:42:45,900
I don't know, Gus.
I think this thing has legs.

678
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:49,400
Maybe I go out with the cops.
Watch 'em warn the homeless.

679
00:42:49,400 --> 00:42:53,100
Good thought, but Alma
can work that into whatever she has.

680
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:04,700
Yeah?

681
00:43:07,700 --> 00:43:09,100
Busy?

682
00:43:09,200 --> 00:43:11,400
No, just...

683
00:43:14,200 --> 00:43:16,200
Jimmy's not in yet.

684
00:43:16,300 --> 00:43:18,900
I know. He's sleeping one off.

685
00:43:20,500 --> 00:43:23,400
- Late night, huh?
- They're all like that now.

686
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:27,400
Relax, I'm not looking for a snitch.

687
00:43:27,400 --> 00:43:29,900
I know you're his partner in crime.
I don't care.

688
00:43:29,900 --> 00:43:31,100
Whoa, Beadie.

689
00:43:31,100 --> 00:43:33,600
I just want to know from you
where this is going.

690
00:43:33,600 --> 00:43:37,500
I mean, you know him.
You know what he can and can't do.

691
00:43:37,500 --> 00:43:39,200
Don't know if I can speak on that.

692
00:43:39,200 --> 00:43:43,000
Look, I'm ready to put him out, OK?
For me, for my kids...

693
00:43:43,700 --> 00:43:46,300
I mean, if in the end,
if this is all there is to him.

694
00:43:46,400 --> 00:43:49,400
If he can't be better than this,
I just want to know.

695
00:43:49,500 --> 00:43:54,800
He's working this case right now.
Serial killer, actually.

696
00:43:54,900 --> 00:43:59,300
Don't tell me this is about a case.
Try that shit on some civilian.

697
00:43:59,300 --> 00:44:02,700
Look, he'll get his head in a certain place,
he'll take a drink.

698
00:44:02,700 --> 00:44:04,800
I mean, a lot of us will.

699
00:44:04,900 --> 00:44:09,000
- It's more than a drink he's taking.
- Beadie, I can't tell you what to do.

700
00:44:13,800 --> 00:44:15,800
I don't like giving up.

701
00:44:20,100 --> 00:44:23,300
OK, I gotta go back to work.
Thanks for letting me vent.

702
00:44:31,500 --> 00:44:33,300
You want to get started today?

703
00:44:33,400 --> 00:44:35,900
- Sooner we decide on...
- After lunch, yeah.

704
00:45:24,600 --> 00:45:26,700
Finally found a line, huh?

705
00:45:26,700 --> 00:45:29,400
Know that wasn't easy.
They been hidin' for years.

706
00:45:29,500 --> 00:45:32,000
- I'm a pro.
- Me, too.

707
00:45:33,100 --> 00:45:34,600
Let me ask you...

708
00:45:35,700 --> 00:45:37,500
When do the results come back?

709
00:45:38,500 --> 00:45:40,700
About an hour from this test.

710
00:45:40,700 --> 00:45:41,700
There you go.

711
00:45:41,800 --> 00:45:47,200
And they want you to believe
that there's only one side to this story,

712
00:45:47,200 --> 00:45:50,600
and that their so-called facts
cannot be denied.

713
00:45:50,700 --> 00:45:54,400
But we have some facts
of our own, don't we?

714
00:45:54,400 --> 00:45:55,600
Yeah!

715
00:45:55,600 --> 00:45:57,900
We know who our leaders are.

716
00:45:57,900 --> 00:46:02,000
And we don't want them picking
our leaders for us, do we?

717
00:46:02,100 --> 00:46:03,300
No!

718
00:46:03,300 --> 00:46:07,400
And we will not stand idly by
as they single out our leaders

719
00:46:07,400 --> 00:46:09,800
and selectively prosecute -

720
00:46:09,800 --> 00:46:11,900
or should I say persecute them -

721
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:16,600
just because they have the courage
and the fortitude to stand up for us.

722
00:46:18,900 --> 00:46:20,500
Let them hear you.

723
00:46:20,500 --> 00:46:23,200
Let them hear you loud and clear.

724
00:46:24,700 --> 00:46:28,200
Clay Davis isn't going anywhere, is he?

725
00:46:28,300 --> 00:46:29,500
No!

726
00:46:29,600 --> 00:46:32,700
We need him,
we're going to keep him,

727
00:46:32,800 --> 00:46:35,900
and damn anyone who says otherwise.

728
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:37,500
Clay Davis!

729
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:47,300
What the fuck is this
I hear about you might not stand tall on this?

730
00:46:47,400 --> 00:46:50,200
You got that wrong, old friend.
I'm gonna carry this.

